 BEGIN_SOLUTION
$PAR Solution $PAR

There are many ways to approach this problem. One approach is to note that the points in the scatter plot fall on a line. To find a linear function to help you predict the cost of shipping 10 pairs of shoes, you would have to find the slope and the y-intercept.
$BR
Using the points (2, 8) and (4,14) we can calculate the slope of the line,  

\(slope = \frac{ 14 - 8 } { 4 - 2} = 3 \).

$BR

Now we need to find the y-intercept. We know that every linear function is of the form 
\( y = mx +b \).
We also know that (2,8) satisfies this equation. This will help us find b: 
\( 8 = 3(2) + b \), 
So b = 2. 

$BR

Now we can make a prediction for how much it would cost to send 10 shoes: 
\( 3(10) + 2 = 32 \)


